author: Meredith Deliso
title: 17-year-old murder suspect accused of shooting 2 teens at his home - ABC News
text:
The booking photo for Connor Hilton. Galveston County Sheriff's Office A Texas teenager accused of shooting two people at his home, one fatally, allegedly told police that he wanted to "commit a homicide for a long time," according to newly released court documents.
The suspect -- 17-year-old Connor Hilton -- was showing the two victims a revolver at his Friendswood home Saturday night when he allegedly shot them both in the head, according to a complaint charging the teen with murder.
A third person who was at the house that night called 911 while hiding in the bathroom and reported hearing two gunshots, according to the complaint.
The booking photo for Connor Hilton. Galveston County Sheriff's Office Responding officers found Hilton outside the home appearing "visibly distraught," the complaint stated. When asked by police if anyone was hurt, Hilton nodded yes then held up two fingers, motioned toward the house and said there were two teenagers inside he believed to be dead, according to the complaint.
Once inside, an officer found two male victims -- identified as Ethan Riley, 18, and Benjamin Bliek, 19 -- lying on the floor with gunshot wounds as well as a revolver on a table, according to the complaint.
A second officer located the 911 caller, who "reported hearing Hilton walk by the bathroom door crying and stating, 'What have I done,'" the complaint stated.
MORE: Body believed to be missing pregnant teen found with gunshot wound: Police
The shooting victims were transported to local hospitals in critical condition. Riley succumbed to his injuries on Sunday, while Bliek remains in critical condition, police said.
Hilton was brought in for questioning following the shooting and was initially charged by the Galveston County District Attorney's Office with two counts of aggravated assault causing serious bodily injury.
He was released after posting $1 million bond before being arrested again at his home on Monday for murder, police said. He is currently being held at the Galveston County Jail on no bond.
Connor Hilton is seen being taken into custody in Friendswood, Texas, on Dec. 25, 2023. KTRK While being interviewed by police following the shooting, Hilton allegedly confessed to pulling the trigger and said there was no disturbance or disagreement that night, according to the complaint.
He allegedly told police "he had thought about, and wanted, to commit a homicide for a long time," according to the complaint. He allegedly said he had talked his mother into buying him a handgun, which he wanted "with the intent of shooting someone and/or himself," according to the complaint.
"Hilton stated that he fully understands what he had done and that he should be held accountable," the complaint stated.
MORE: Florida mall shooting: Reward up to $10,000 as police hunt for suspect
Hilton's attorney, Jennifer Carpenter, told ABC News that his mother did not purchase a gun for him.
"The parents of Connor Hilton cannot express enough their deepest condolences to the victims' families who have been heavily on the Hiltons' hearts and minds as they try to navigate this devastating situation," Hilton's family said in a statement released through the attorney on Thursday.
"The Hilton family wants to thank everyone who has reached out in love and support, including all who sent positive comments about Connor's character and good nature in general," the statement continued. "The family asks for continued prayers for everyone affected, especially the victims' families."
His attorney has filed a motion seeking to conduct a hearing to determine whether his statements to police can be admissible in court, claiming they were not made and preserved in compliance with state law.
Hilton is scheduled to appear in court for a status conference on Feb. 2, online court records show.

title: 'Failing at their job': Zoho founder Sridhar Vembu on programmers submitting AI-generated code without reviewing it - The Economic Times
text: Zoho founder Sridhar Vembu has shared an account of how he currently uses artificial intelligence, describing it as a powerful tool for learning and critical thinking. At the same time, he warned against becoming overly reliant on it.In a post on X, Vembu called himself a moderate to heavy user of AI, and went on to outline his thoughts on its strengths and limitations.According to Vembu, AI has proven to be a far superior learning aid than traditional web search. “My web search has gone down 80% as a direct result,” he wrote, explaining how AI helps him learn faster.He also highlighted how AI serves as a “good debating partner”, adding that he often takes the output from one AI and asks another to critique it. This, he said, helps deepen his understanding.However, his praise for the technology came with some strong warnings.He advised against using AI to create new content. “AI can help customer support agents do their work faster but it is unwise to let AI replace human agents. It is also unwise for a human to copy-paste AI text and send it to a customer, hiding the fact that it came from AI.”On the topic of programming, Vembu stressed that any AI-generated code must go through thorough checks for compliance, privacy, and security. These checks, he admitted, are “neither easy nor fun for humans to do”.He also opined that programmers who submit AI-generated code without carrying out these checks are “failing at their job”. He went so far as to say that AI could sometimes slow down the development process.Vembu then encouraged Zoho programmers to use AI as a tool for learning and exploration, rather than as a shortcut for generating unchecked content or delivering code.He concluded by saying the company is “running a lot of experiments” and that his perspective may shift over time as “facts change on the ground”.

author: Brian Neeley
title: Young 3PL set to add 20 jobs in 2024 despite tough market - Business News
text: (Photo: Jim Allen/FreightWaves) Wagon founders Robert Rajfar and Tyler Sala set out to build a 3PL characterized by integrity and a genuine dedication to best-in-class customer service. Following a successful fourth quarter, the company is looking toward its 2024 goals – from enhancing its instantiation capabilities to establishing itself as a partner in food and beverage, HAZMAT and other high-value spaces. To accomplish these goals, Rajfar and Sala are looking to add several like-minded logistics professionals to their sales and customer success teams. Overall, the company plans to add 20 jobs in the coming year. For those interested in positions at Wagon, it's important to understand what the company means by “best-in-class customer service.” “Everyone says they're customer-centric, but no one talks about what that actually means,” said Pat Stradinger, vice president of customer success at Waggon. Rajfer's definition of “best-in-class customer experience” means being readily available, offering fair but competitive prices, and having an owner's mentality. He said it is important for the entire organization, not just the leadership team, to stick with the same set of customer-first values. Most of all, it's important for new Wagan employees to be curious and excited to learn. “I had a lot of success early in my career when I became more curious,” Salas said. Curious people have a natural desire to look deeper, making them more inclined to gain knowledge about how supply chains work on a global scale. This change in perspective is called moving from A to B thinking to A to Z thinking. Wagon wants to hire A to Z thinkers. In addition to being curious and dedicated to customer service, all Wagon Teammates must be excited to help build a company from the ground up. This work requires a far higher level of patience than more corporate positions – and a far more developed ability to wear multiple hats within the organization. “We're looking for serious individuals, people who have been in the trenches,” Stradinger said. “We want to know that our customers are interacting with experts.” Wagon wants to hear from people who agree with this description – especially curious, serious logistics professionals who have a solid base of industry knowledge and a desire to create something new. author: sina.com.cn
title: 专家长期驻扎 患者"回流"基层|王江_新浪财经_新浪网
text:
转自：嘉兴日报
　　■记者 钟淑婷 通讯员 肖易张博
　　本报讯 “在家门口就能享受专家技术，方便！”近日，在秀洲区王江泾医院，一名桡骨远端骨折患者用自己的就医选择，诠释了医联体建设的显著成效。
　　这名患者因意外导致桡骨远端骨折，原本已在市级医院办好住院手续，准备接受手术。但在了解到浙江省荣军医院骨科主任医师翁科迪长期驻扎在王江泾医院坐诊手术后，经过与医生的充分沟通和专业评估，他选择转入王江泾医院进行治疗。这一选择，不仅是对翁科迪主任医师的高度信任，更是对基层医疗服务提升的有力认可。
　　手术当日，翁科迪带领基层外科团队，凭借丰富的临床经验与精湛技术，顺利完成骨折复位内固定手术。这场“上级诊断+基层治疗”的创新实践，保障了手术质量，更让患者切实享受到多重实惠：相比市级医院，住院费用降低，同时免去往返奔波之苦，真正实现“家门口看名医”。
　　这样的案例并非个例。自今年3月省荣军医院与王江泾医院正式建立医联体合作关系以来，通过建立专家常态化驻点机制，像翁科迪这样的省荣军医院骨干力量深入基层，为患者带来了高水平的诊疗服务。同时，“传帮带”模式也在悄然发挥作用，推动优质医疗服务向基层延伸。就在前不久，在省荣军医院呼吸科陈芹主任团队的指导下，王江泾医院还成功完成了一台极具挑战性的气管镜下活检手术。
　　“把专家送到群众身边，让技术留在基层医院。”王江泾医院相关负责人满怀期待地表示，随着医联体建设的持续深入推进，未来将会有更多患者享受到“家门口看名医”的便捷服务，让优质医疗资源真正惠及每一位群众，为大家的健康生活筑牢坚实保障。

author: BFMTV
title: Braquage d'une bijouterie à Nantes : les cambrioleurs passent par le plafond pour voler des milliers d'euros
text:
BFMTV Braquage d'une bijouterie à Nantes : les cambrioleurs passent par le plafond pour voler des milliers d'euros Un braquage d'une bijouterie a eu lieu à Nantes. La méthode des malfaiteurs interpelle : selon les premiers éléments, ils se seraient créé un passage en perçant un trou dans le plancher de l'appartement situé au-dessus du commerce. A.G 13 juin 2024 à 11:42 PM Lien copié
Une bijouterie du centre-ville de Nantes a été victime ce jeudi 13 juin d'un vol par effraction après le "percement d'un plancher", a-t-on appris auprès du parquet, confirmant une information de Presse Océan . Selon le procureur de la République de Nantes, Renaud Gaudeul, le montant du préjudice était en cours d'évaluation jeudi après-midi. Le journal local indique qu'il pourrait s’élever à plusieurs dizaines de milliers d’euros.
Une enquête ouverte Prévenues vers 7 heures par l'agence de sécurité en charge de la surveillance de la boutique, les forces de l'ordre ne constataient sur place "la présence d'aucun individu mais découvraient un début d'incendie au deuxième étage" de l'immeuble, a expliqué Renaud Gaudeul.
Une fois l'incendie maîtrisé par les services de secours, "il était alors constaté l'effraction de locaux situés au deuxième étage et le percement d'un plancher permettant d'accéder aux locaux de la bijouterie", selon la même source.
À l'intérieur de la boutique, plusieurs vitrines contenant "des montres et des bijoux" ont été brisées.
Une enquête a été ouverte des chefs de vol par effraction et destruction par incendie, et confiée à la division de la criminalité organisée et spécialisée de la DTPN (Direction territoriale de la police nationale) de Nantes.
Article original publié sur BFMTV.com
